  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Methodologies Detail Reference</title>
    <summary>A flat reference page bundling 20 research methodologies as a human-readable cheat sheet and an agent routing index. Each entry lists framework keywords, scoring thresholds, and the agent mode that activates the canonical methodology folder under pro/research/researcher/, pro/research/market-researcher/, or pro/research/user-researcher/.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Large research codebases benefit from one skim-readable page that lists every methodology, its core framework, and the agent mode that routes to it. This page serves that role for humans scanning the suite and for agents performing first-pass mode resolution before loading the canonical methodology file.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Human wants a quick overview of all 20 research methodologies and their agent modes in one place</item>
        <item>Agent received an ambiguous research request and needs to map keywords to a mode before loading the canonical folder</item>
        <item>Generating a TOC, sidebar, or cross-reference for documentation</item>
        <item>Sanity-checking that a methodology exists in the suite before referencing it</item>
        <item>Composing a multi-method research plan (e.g. mode=ideas then mode=validate then mode=market)</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>As the execution reference for any specific methodology — open the methodology's own folder for full content</item>
        <item>For prompt templates, full scoring rubrics, or agent integration code — those live in per-methodology files</item>
        <item>For mode routing inside an orchestrator at runtime — use the Research Modes table in the parent CLAUDE.md, not this page</item>
        <item>To copy abridged scoring thresholds into production decisions — always verify against the canonical methodology</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="reference-usage">
      <rules>
        <rule>
          <statement>Treat this page as a TOC and routing cheat-sheet only. Do not parse it as the source of truth for any single methodology.</statement>
          <rationale>Every entry is abridged. Scoring weights, decision thresholds, and step lists are summaries. Production decisions must load the canonical methodology.xml in the per-methodology folder.</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>Resolve a request to exactly one agent mode before loading content.</statement>
          <rationale>Mode determines which folder the agent reads next. Multiple matches are allowed only when the orchestrator explicitly chains modes (ideas → validate → market).</rationale>
        </rule>
        <rule>
          <statement>If an entry on this page conflicts with the canonical methodology file, the canonical file wins.</statement>
          <rationale>This page is updated less frequently than per-methodology files. Treat any divergence as drift to fix in this page, not in the canonical file.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </rules>
    </section>
    <how-to>
      <step>Read the user request and extract intent keywords (idea, market, competitor, user, persona, pricing, name, niche, validate).</step>
      <step>Match keywords to one of the agent modes listed below using the routing table.</step>
      <step>Open the canonical methodology folder for that mode (e.g. mode=market → pro/research/market-researcher/market-research-tam-sam-som/methodology.xml).</step>
      <step>Apply the canonical methodology end-to-end. Do not improvise from the abridged summary on this page.</step>
      <step>Write the named output file under .aidocs/product_docs/ as specified in the parent CLAUDE.md.</step>
      <step>Cross-link to peer methodologies if the orchestrator runs a multi-mode chain.</step>
    </how-to>
    <section name="routing-table">
      <p>Mode → output → canonical folder mapping. Use this table for first-pass routing.</p>
      <list>
        <item>ideas → idea-candidates.md → market-researcher/idea-generation, market-researcher/paul-graham-questions, user-researcher/pain-point-research</item>
        <item>niche → niche-evaluation.md → market-researcher/niche-evaluation, market-researcher/niche-viability-scoring, market-researcher/business-model-research</item>
        <item>market → market-research.md → market-researcher/market-research-tam-sam-som, market-researcher/trend-analysis</item>
        <item>competitors → competitive-analysis.md → market-researcher/competitor-analysis, market-researcher/competitive-intelligence</item>
        <item>validate → problem-validation.md → user-researcher/user-interviews, user-researcher/problem-validation, user-researcher/customer-interview-framework</item>
        <item>personas → user-personas.md → user-researcher/jobs-to-be-done, user-researcher/persona-building, market-researcher/value-proposition-design</item>
        <item>pains → pain-points.md → user-researcher/pain-point-mining</item>
        <item>pricing → pricing-research.md → market-researcher/pricing-research</item>
        <item>names → name-candidates.md → market-researcher/project-naming, market-researcher/domain-availability</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="idea-generation-methods">
      <p>Idea generation and screening methodologies (mode=ideas):</p>
      <list>
        <item>idea-generation — 7 Ps framework (Pain, Passion, Profession, Process, Platform, People, Product). Score each idea: Market size + Your fit + Urgency, max 15. Top 3 scores proceed to validation. Agent mode: ideas.</item>
        <item>paul-graham-questions — 4 questions: What is tedious but necessary? What is surprisingly hard? What do you build for yourself? What would you pay for that does not exist? Agent mode: ideas.</item>
        <item>pain-point-research — Complaint audit, workaround inventory, tool stack analysis, time tracker. Score: frequency 30%, intensity 30%, current solutions 20%, ability to solve 20%. Agent mode: ideas.</item>
        <item>niche-evaluation — 5-dimension scoring: Market size, Competition, Barriers, Monetization, Your fit (1-5 each, max 25). Proceed: 20-25. Caution: 15-19. Needs pivot: 10-14. Pass: below 10. Agent mode: niche.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="market-analysis">
      <p>Market analysis and competitive intelligence methodologies (mode=market, mode=competitors):</p>
      <list>
        <item>market-research-tam-sam-som — TAM (total addressable), SAM (serviceable), SOM (obtainable Year 1). Three methods: top-down, bottom-up, value theory. SOM typically 1-5% of SAM. Agent mode: market.</item>
        <item>trend-analysis — Macro (5-10yr), industry (2-5yr), micro (6-24mo) trend categories. Assess: growth drivers, adoption curve position, threats, timing (too early / just right / too late). Agent mode: market.</item>
        <item>competitor-analysis — Identify direct, indirect, future competitors. Map on positioning matrix. Analyse 8 dimensions. Find gaps (feature, quality, audience, price, experience). Differentiation statement. Agent mode: competitors.</item>
        <item>competitive-intelligence — Feature inventory across top 5 competitors. Feature matrix (Y/P/N per competitor). Gap categories: nobody has it, 1-2 have it (opportunity), everyone has it (table stakes). Validate gap before building. Agent mode: competitors.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="user-research">
      <p>User research and validation methodologies (mode=validate, mode=personas, mode=pains):</p>
      <list>
        <item>user-interviews — Problem, solution, usability interview types. 45-min structure: warm-up, current state, pain exploration, solution probing, wrap-up. Golden rules: talk less than 20%, ask about past behaviour not future intent. Agent mode: validate.</item>
        <item>jobs-to-be-done — JTBD statement: When I [situation], I want to [action], so I can [outcome]. Three job dimensions: functional, emotional, social. Hiring and firing framework. Agent mode: personas.</item>
        <item>persona-building — 5 components: demographics, behaviours, pain points, goals, verbatim quote. Types: primary, secondary, negative. Minimum 5-10 interviews before building. Agent mode: personas.</item>
        <item>problem-validation — 5 criteria: frequency weekly or more, intensity 7+/10, willingness to pay, search volume exists, competition exists. Evidence types: verbatim quotes (strong), forum discussions (medium), competitor existence (weak). Agent mode: validate.</item>
        <item>pain-point-mining — Sources: Reddit, Twitter, app reviews, Quora, forums, LinkedIn. Search patterns: "[keyword] frustrating" site:reddit.com, "[competitor] alternative" site:reddit.com. Collect 50+ mentions, categorize by theme, count frequency. Agent mode: pains.</item>
        <item>customer-interview-framework — 4 interview types by stage: discovery, problem, solution, usability. Flow: warm-up, context, deep dive, concept test, wrap-up. Question types: open, probing, clarifying, summary. Anti-patterns: leading questions, future hypotheticals, pitching. Agent mode: validate.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="business-model-planning">
      <p>Business model and pricing research methodologies (mode=niche, mode=personas, mode=pricing):</p>
      <list>
        <item>niche-viability-scoring — 5-criteria weighted model: Market size 25%, Competition 20%, Barriers 20%, Profitability 20%, Your fit 15%. Score 1-10 with justification. Decision thresholds: 7.5 or higher strong, 5.5-7.4 caution, 3.5-5.4 risks, below 3.5 pass. Agent mode: niche.</item>
        <item>business-model-research — Red vs Blue Ocean. Four actions framework: Eliminate, Reduce, Raise, Create. Strategy canvas: X-axis key competing factors, Y-axis offering level. Find uncontested space. Agent mode: niche.</item>
        <item>value-proposition-design — Customer profile: jobs, pains, gains. Value map: products/services, pain relievers, gain creators. FIT equals pain relievers address top pains plus gain creators enable top gains. Focus on pains rated 8+/10. Agent mode: personas.</item>
        <item>pricing-research — Six models: freemium, subscription, usage-based, one-time, tiered, per-seat. Selection criteria: value delivery, usage patterns, customer type, competition, marginal cost. Research: list 5 competitors pricing, calculate value delivered, Van Westendorp survey, test with early users. Agent mode: pricing.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="naming-and-domains">
      <p>Naming and domain availability methodologies (mode=names):</p>
      <list>
        <item>project-naming — 7 strategies: descriptive, invented, compound, metaphor, portmanteau, alliteration, acronym. Good name criteria: easy to spell, pronounce, memorable, domain available (.com preferred), no trademark conflicts, works internationally. Generate 20+ candidates before checking availability. Agent mode: names.</item>
        <item>domain-availability — Check priority: .com (essential), .io (acceptable for tech), .co (alternative), GitHub username, Twitter handle, LinkedIn page. Alternative strategies: add "get" or "try" prefix, "app" or "hq" suffix, different TLD. Agent: faion-domain-checker-agent.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <checklist>
      <check>Confirm the agent mode resolves to exactly one of: ideas, niche, market, competitors, validate, personas, pains, pricing, names.</check>
      <check>Open the canonical per-methodology folder for that mode and read methodology.xml end-to-end before applying.</check>
      <check>Verify the named output file path under .aidocs/product_docs/ matches the routing table on this page.</check>
      <check>Do not invent scoring thresholds — always copy them from the canonical methodology, not this abridged page.</check>
      <check>If multiple methodologies share a mode (e.g. ideas has 3), pick the one that best matches the request keywords; chain only when the orchestrator says so.</check>
      <check>If the user request mentions a methodology name not on this page, search the wider faion-network/skills tree before declaring it missing.</check>
      <check>Cite the canonical methodology slug in the output file footer for traceability.</check>
      <check>If this page disagrees with the canonical methodology, update this page after finishing the task — never edit the canonical file to match this page.</check>
    </checklist>
    <commands>
      <command name="list-canonical-folders">find skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research -maxdepth 4 -name methodology.xml | sort</command>
      <command name="grep-mode-keywords">grep -RIl "Agent mode:" skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research</command>
      <command name="open-canonical">cat skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/market-researcher/market-research-tam-sam-som/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="validate-this-page">python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/researcher/methodologies-detail/methodology.xml</command>
      <command name="list-output-targets">ls .aidocs/product_docs/ 2&gt;/dev/null || echo "no product_docs yet — orchestrator will create it"</command>
    </commands>
    <prompt purpose="resolve-mode-from-request"><![CDATA[
You are routing a research request to one of these modes:
  ideas | niche | market | competitors | validate | personas | pains | pricing | names

User request:
{{ USER_REQUEST }}

Return JSON only:
{
  "mode": "<one of the modes above>",
  "canonical_folder": "skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/<sub-skill>/<methodology-slug>/",
  "output_file": ".aidocs/product_docs/<file>.md",
  "rationale": "<one sentence keyword match>"
}

Routing keywords:
- ideas: idea, brainstorm, "what to build", opportunity
- niche: niche, vertical, segment fit, viability
- market: TAM, SAM, SOM, market size, trend, adoption curve
- competitors: competitor, alternative, feature matrix, positioning
- validate: validate, interview, problem confirmation, willingness to pay
- personas: persona, JTBD, jobs-to-be-done, value proposition
- pains: pain, frustration, complaint mining, Reddit search
- pricing: price, pricing model, freemium, Van Westendorp
- names: name, naming, domain, .com availability
]]></prompt>
    <template path="output-header.md.j2"><![CDATA[
# {{ TITLE }}

- mode: {{ MODE }}
- canonical_methodology: {{ CANONICAL_SLUG }}
- canonical_path: {{ CANONICAL_PATH }}
- generated_by: faion-research-agent
- generated_at: {{ ISO_DATE }}

## Inputs

- request: {{ USER_REQUEST }}
- chain (if multi-mode): {{ MODE_CHAIN | default("none") }}

## Findings

(Populate by applying the canonical methodology. Do not paraphrase the abridged TOC — load the full methodology.xml first.)

## Decision

(Apply the canonical methodology's scoring rubric. Cite thresholds verbatim from the canonical file.)

## References

- Canonical methodology: {{ CANONICAL_PATH }}
- TOC entry: skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/researcher/methodologies-detail/methodology.xml
]]></template>
    <verify>
      <step>Run python3 scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py on this file. Output must say PASS / OK with zero errors.</step>
      <step>Confirm every section in this page (idea-generation-methods, market-analysis, user-research, business-model-planning, naming-and-domains) lists 4-6 methodologies that exist as folders under skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/.</step>
      <step>For each methodology listed, run: test -f skills/faion/knowledge/pro/research/&lt;sub&gt;/&lt;slug&gt;/methodology.xml. Every test must succeed.</step>
      <step>Run the resolve-mode prompt against three sample requests ("how do I price my SaaS", "find me a niche", "validate my problem") and confirm the model returns valid JSON with one of the nine documented modes.</step>
      <step>Confirm the routing-table mode list (ideas, niche, market, competitors, validate, personas, pains, pricing, names) matches the parent CLAUDE.md Research Modes table exactly.</step>
      <step>If any verify step fails, fix this page (never the canonical methodology) and re-run validation.</step>
    </verify>
    <see-also>
      <ref slug="market-research-tam-sam-som"/>
      <ref slug="competitor-analysis"/>
      <ref slug="problem-validation"/>
      <ref slug="persona-building"/>
